article.description: With the game on the line, Kansas State's big guns took charge.
article.headline: In foul trouble, Ohlde still notches double-double
article.linkText: Scoring bursts give K-State win over Colorado
article.story:
BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- With the game on the line, Kansas State's
big guns took charge.

Kendra Wecker had 23 points and 11 rebounds and hit three key
baskets down the stretch, leading No. 12 Kansas State to a 76-69
win over No. 14 Colorado on Saturday.

Kansas State (11-2, 2-0 Big 12) also got 19 points from Laurie
Koehn and 17 points and 10 rebounds from Nicole Ohlde, who sat out
most of the first half with foul trouble.

Playing the entire second half, Ohlde had 11 points and nine
rebounds, including six offensive rebounds which resulted in three
layups.

"I thought Nicole really made some statement plays with her
offensive and defensive rebounds," Kansas State coach Deb
Patterson said. "Kendra and Laurie each played 40 minutes and
stepped up at real critical junctures of the game."

Tera Bjorklund had 22 points and eight rebounds for Colorado
(12-2, 1-1).

Kansas State, posting its ninth straight victory, used a 10-3
run in the second half to open a 71-65 lead with 4:30 remaining.
Wecker and Koehn hit 3-pointers to start the burst, and Wecker's
spin move in the lane made it 69-64 with 5:00 to go.

Ohlde's rebound layup gave KSU a 71-65 lead.

Layups by Bjorklund and Amber Metoyer cut it to 71-69, but
Wecker made a driving layup for a 73-69 lead with 1:25 left.

"I was able to penetrate the lane a couple of times and hit
some runners and layups," Wecker said. "With the way they were
pressuring on the perimeter, I was able to take it strong to the
hole.

"To come on the road in a very tough environment and get a win,
I think it says a lot about our team, that we're going to be
competitive and aggressive in the Big 12."

Colorado was forced to foul in the final minute, and the
Wildcats hit 3-of-5 free throws.

"I think the difference in the game was the 12 offensive
rebounds Kansas State got in the second half," Colorado coach Ceal
Barry said. "They knew when to turn it on. Wecker and Koehn hit
big 3s, and Wecker hit another 2 in that stretch where they went
ahead. We had kept them at bay to that point, but their studs kind
of took over.

"I'm very disappointed. It was a good opportunity that we let
get away."

Bjorklund had 12 points in the first half and Wecker 14 as
Colorado took a 40-38 halftime lead.

The Buffaloes, whose nine-game winning streak was snapped, used
a 16-4 run to forge a 19-11 lead. Emily Waner had back-to-back
3-pointers, and Bjorklund had a three-point play during the surge.

Ohlde picked up her second foul with 13:20 left and didn't play
the remainder of the half, but the Wildcats got solid play from
their bench.

Koehn had a 3-pointer and a three-point play to help cut the
deficit to two points. Colorado responded with Kate Fagan's 3-point
basket and Bjorklund's three-point play, making it 30-22.

Back-to-back 3-pointers by Wecker and Koehn reduced the deficit
to two, and Wecker's two free throws produced a 32-32 tie with 3:43
left.
